\begin_layout Enumerate

\shape smallcaps
Derivations and comparing posterior distributions (
\shape default
\emph on
Total credits: 17p
\shape smallcaps
\emph default
)
\shape default

\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Problems (a), (b) and (c) should only be solved on 
\series bold
\color blue
Paper
\series default
\color inherit
.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x|\theta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right),$
\end_inset

 be an independent sample from a binomial distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Bin}(N,\theta)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is known and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\left(x_{i}|\theta\right)={N \choose x_{i}}\theta^{x_{i}}\left(1-\theta\right)^{N-x_{i}},\;0<\theta<1,\;x_{i}=0,1,2,\dots,N,\;i=1,\dots,n.
\]

\end_inset

Assume the following conjugate beta prior for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 with parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=3$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\theta\right)=\frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha+\beta\right)}{\Gamma\left(\alpha\right)\Gamma\left(\beta\right)}\theta^{\alpha-1}\left(1-\theta\right)^{\beta-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits: 3p.

\emph default
 Derive the posterior distribution for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits
\emph default
: 
\emph on
2p
\emph default
.
 Compute the Bayes point estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=13,x_{2}=8,x_{3}=11,x_{4}=7$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N=20$
\end_inset

 by assuming the zero-one loss function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits: 5p.

\emph default
 Derive the posterior predictive density of a new observation 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n+1}$
\end_inset

.
 An expression is enough, you don't need to recognize any distributional
 family from the end result.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits: 4p.

\emph default
 Write a function in R that computes the log posterior distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 as the sum of the log likelihood and the log prior distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 for an independent sample 
\begin_inset Formula $x|\theta$
\end_inset

.
 Then, use this function to plot the posterior distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 based on the data in 1(b).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Credits: 3p.

\emph default
 Use numerical optimization to obtain a normal approximation to the posterior
 distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 based on the data in 1(b).
 Use the 
\family typewriter
lines
\family default
 command in R to plot this approximate posterior in the same graph as the
 posterior obtained in 1(d).
 [Hints: use the argument 
\family typewriter
lower=0.2
\family default
 in 
\family typewriter
optim
\family default
, and 
\family typewriter
method=c("L-BFGS-B")
\family default
].
 Is the posterior approximation accurate?
