\emph default
 Now consider two independent Poisson models, one for the observation weeks
 in region A and one for the observation weeks in region B.
 These two models can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{A,i}|\theta_{A}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}\text{Poisson}\left(\theta_{A}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{B,i}|\theta_{B}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}\text{Poisson}\left(\theta_{B}\right)$
\end_inset

, where the subscripts indicate which observations and parameters that correspon
d to the observation weeks in region A or B.
 Use the same prior as in (a) for both 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Do posterior inference in both models.
 Calculate the probability that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{B,j}>y_{A,j}$
\end_inset

 on a randomly picked future week 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

